# C# / .NET Rules

## Language and Types
- Enable nullable reference types (`<Nullable>enable</Nullable>`). Do not suppress warnings with `!` without justification.
- Use file-scoped namespaces.
- Use records for immutable data transfer objects.
- Prefer `var` when the type is obvious from the right-hand side.

## Async
- Use `async`/`await` for all I/O operations.
- Use `ConfigureAwait(false)` in library code. Omit it in application code (ASP.NET Core).
- Do not use `.Result` or `.Wait()` on tasks. This causes deadlocks.
- Return `Task` or `ValueTask`, not `void`, from async methods (except event handlers).

## Dependency Injection
- Use the built-in DI container. Register services in `Program.cs` or extension methods.
- Prefer constructor injection. Do not use the service locator pattern.
- Use `IOptions<T>` / `IOptionsSnapshot<T>` for configuration, not raw `IConfiguration` access.

## Error Handling
- Use custom exception types for domain errors.
- Use middleware for global exception handling. Do not scatter try/catch in every controller action.
- Return `ProblemDetails` for API error responses.

## Entity Framework Core
- Use migrations for all schema changes. Run `dotnet ef migrations add` and commit the migration files.
- Use `AsNoTracking()` for read-only queries.
- Do not expose `DbContext` outside the data layer. Use a repository or service abstraction.

## Testing
- Use xUnit, NUnit, or MSTest (match the project).
- Use `WebApplicationFactory<T>` for integration tests.
- Use NSubstitute or Moq for mocking. Prefer testing behavior over mocking internals.

## Configuration
- Use `appsettings.json` for defaults, environment variables for overrides.
- Validate configuration at startup with `ValidateDataAnnotations()` or `ValidateOnStart()`.
- Never hardcode connection strings or secrets.
